==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} ''[[cyrin|ċyrin]]''. Cognate with West Frisian {{term|tsjerne|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|karn|lang=nl}} and Walloon {{term|serene|lang=wa}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{enPR|chû(r)n}}, {{IPA|/tʃɜː(r)n/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/tʃɚn/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-churn.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɜː(r)n|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[agitate]] [[rapid]]ly and [[repetitive]]ly, or to [[stir]] with a [[row]]ing or [[rock]]ing motion; generally applies to [[liquid]]s, notably [[cream]].
#: ''Now the cream is '''churned''' to make butter.''
#* Addison
#*: '''Churned''' in his teeth, the foamy venom rose.
# {{context|transitive|figuratively|lang=en}} To [[produce]] [[excessive]] and sometimes [[undesirable]] or [[unproductive]] [[activity]] or [[motion]].
#* {{quote-news|date=2012|author=John Branch|title=Snow Fall : The Avalanche at Tunnel Creek|newspaper=New York Time|url=http://www.nytimes.com/projects/2012/snow-fall/?smid=fb-nytimes&WT.z_sma=SP_SNT_20130415#/?part=tunnel-creek}}
#*: The slope of the terrain, shaped like a funnel, squeezed the growing swell of '''churning''' snow into a steep, twisting gorge.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To move rapidly and repetitively with a rocking motion; to [[tumble]], [[mix]] or [[shake]].
#: ''I was so nervous my stomach was '''churning'''.''

